1. What is Java?

Java is a high-level, object-oriented, platform-independent programming language developed by James Gosling in 1995.

Key Features
Platform Independent ("Write Once, Run Anywhere")
Object-Oriented
Robust
Secure
Multithreaded
Portable
Distributed
Dynamic
Interview Question

Q: Why is Java platform independent?

Answer: Java code is compiled into bytecode, which runs on the JVM (Java Virtual Machine) available for different operating systems.

2. Java Architecture
Java Source Code (.java)
        ↓
Compiler (javac)
        ↓
Bytecode (.class)
        ↓
JVM
        ↓
Machine Code
Components
JDK (Java Development Kit)
Used for development
Contains JRE + Development Tools
JRE (Java Runtime Environment)
Provides runtime environment
Contains JVM + Libraries
JVM (Java Virtual Machine)
Executes bytecode
Interview Question

Q: Difference between JDK, JRE, and JVM?

JDK	JRE	JVM
Development Kit	Runtime Environment	Executes Bytecode
Contains JRE	Contains JVM	Part of JRE
3. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

This is the most important interview topic.

Class

Blueprint of objects.

class Student {
    int id;
}
Object

Instance of a class.

Student s = new Student();
Interview Question

Q: Difference between Class and Object?

Class = Blueprint
Object = Real instance occupying memory
4. Four Pillars of OOP
1. Encapsulation

Wrapping data and methods together.

class Employee {
    private int salary;

    public void setSalary(int salary){
        this.salary = salary;
    }
}
Benefits
Data hiding
Security
2. Inheritance

Acquiring properties of parent class.

class Animal {
    void eat(){}
}

class Dog extends Animal {
}
Types
Single
Multilevel
Hierarchical

(Java does not support multiple inheritance through classes.)

Interview Question

Q: Why doesn't Java support multiple inheritance?

To avoid the Diamond Problem and ambiguity.

3. Polymorphism

One method, multiple forms.

Compile-Time Polymorphism

(Method Overloading)

add(int a,int b)
add(int a,int b,int c)
Run-Time Polymorphism

(Method Overriding)

class Animal{
    void sound(){}
}

class Dog extends Animal{
    void sound(){}
}
Interview Question

Q: Difference between Overloading and Overriding?

Overloading	Overriding
Same class	Parent-child
Compile time	Runtime
Different parameters	Same parameters
4. Abstraction

Hiding implementation details.

Abstract Class
abstract class Vehicle{
    abstract void start();
}
Interface
interface Vehicle{
    void start();
}
Interview Question

Q: Abstract class vs Interface?

Abstract Class	Interface
Can have constructors	No constructors
Partial abstraction	Full abstraction (traditionally)
extends keyword	implements keyword
5. Constructor

Special method used to initialize objects.

class Student{
    Student(){
        System.out.println("Constructor");
    }
}
Types
Default Constructor
Parameterized Constructor
Interview Question

Q: Can constructor be inherited?

No.

6. this and super
this

Refers to current object.

this.id = id;
super

Refers to parent class object.

super.display();
Interview Question

Q: Difference between this and super?

this → current class
super → parent class
7. Static Keyword

Belongs to class, not object.

class Test{
    static int count = 0;
}
Uses
Static variable
Static method
Static block
Interview Question

Q: Can static method access non-static variables?

No, because non-static members require an object.

8. String Concepts
String

Immutable object.

String s = "Hello";
Interview Question

Q: Why is String immutable?

Security
Thread safety
String pool optimization
String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer
Feature	String	StringBuilder	StringBuffer
Mutable	No	Yes	Yes
Thread Safe	No	No	Yes
Performance	Slow	Fast	Moderate
9. Exception Handling

Mechanism to handle runtime errors.

try{
}
catch(Exception e){
}
finally{
}
Types
Checked Exceptions

Checked at compile time.

Example:

IOException
SQLException
Unchecked Exceptions

Runtime exceptions.

Example:

NullPointerException
ArithmeticException
Interview Question

Q: Difference between Checked and Unchecked Exceptions?

Checked exceptions must be handled or declared; unchecked exceptions do not.

10. Collection Framework

Very important for MNC interviews.

List

Ordered and allows duplicates.

ArrayList
Dynamic array
Fast retrieval
LinkedList
Fast insertion/deletion
Set

No duplicates.

HashSet
Unordered
Uses hashing
LinkedHashSet
Maintains insertion order
TreeSet
Sorted order
Map

Stores key-value pairs.

HashMap
Unordered
Allows one null key
LinkedHashMap
Maintains insertion order
TreeMap
Sorted by keys
Interview Question

Q: HashMap vs Hashtable?

HashMap	Hashtable
Not synchronized	Synchronized
Faster	Slower
Allows null key	No null key
11. Multithreading

Executing multiple threads simultaneously.

class MyThread extends Thread{
    public void run(){
    }
}
Thread Lifecycle
New
Runnable
Running
Waiting
Terminated
Interview Question

Q: Difference between start() and run()?

start() creates a new thread
run() executes in the current thread
12. Memory Management
Stack Memory
Local variables
Method calls
Heap Memory
Objects
Instance variables
Interview Question

Q: Where are objects stored?

Heap memory.

13. Garbage Collection

Automatically removes unused objects.

System.gc();
Interview Question

Q: Can we force garbage collection?

No. We can request it using System.gc(), but JVM decides.

14. Access Modifiers
Modifier	Same Class	Same Package	Subclass	Other Package
private	Yes	No	No	No
default	Yes	Yes	No	No
protected	Yes	Yes	Yes	No*
public	Yes	Yes	Yes	Yes
15. Important Java 8 Features
Lambda Expression
(a,b) -> a+b
Stream API
list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x > 10)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
Functional Interface
@FunctionalInterface
interface Test{
    void show();
}
Interview Question

Q: What is a Functional Interface?

An interface with exactly one abstract method.

